# Code Style Rules

## General Principles
- Write clear, readable code over clever code
- Use descriptive variable and function names
- Keep functions small and focused (single responsibility)
- Comment complex logic, especially business rules

## TypeScript / JavaScript

### Naming
- Use camelCase for variables and functions: `getUserData`, `isActive`
- Use PascalCase for components and classes: `ContractList`, `UserService`
- Use UPPER_SNAKE_CASE for constants: `MAX_FILE_SIZE`, `API_TIMEOUT`
- Prefix boolean variables with is/has/should: `isLoading`, `hasError`

### Functions
- Use arrow functions for callbacks and inline functions
- Use async/await over .then() chains
- Always handle errors in async functions
- Return early to reduce nesting

### Example
```typescript
// Good: Clear naming, async/await, early return, typed
const fetchContracts = async (status: string): Promise<Contract[]> => {
  if (!status) return [];
  
  try {
    const { data, error } = await supabase
      .from('contracts')
      .select('*')
      .eq('status', status);
    
    if (error) throw error;
    return data ?? [];
  } catch (err) {
    console.error('Failed to fetch contracts:', err);
    return [];
  }
};
```

## Next.js Components

### Structure
- 'use client' directive at top (only if needed)
- Imports at top (external, then internal)
- Component definition
- Helper functions inside or extracted
- Export at bottom (default export for pages)

### Client Components (Hooks Order)
1. useState declarations
2. useQuery / useMutation (TanStack Query)
3. useEffect for side effects
4. Custom hooks
5. Event handlers
6. Render helpers
7. Return JSX

### Example (Client Component with TanStack Query + Shadcn/ui)
```tsx
'use client';

import { useContracts } from '@/lib/queries';
import { Card, CardContent, CardHeader, CardTitle } from '@/components/ui/card';
import { Table, TableBody, TableCell, TableRow } from '@/components/ui/table';
import { Badge } from '@/components/ui/badge';
import { Loader2 } from 'lucide-react';
import type { Database } from '@/types/database.types';

type Contract = Database['public']['Tables']['contracts']['Row'];

interface ContractListProps {
  onSelect: (contract: Contract) => void;
}

export default function ContractList({ onSelect }: ContractListProps) {
  const { data: contracts, isLoading, error } = useContracts();

  if (isLoading) {
    return (
      <div className="flex items-center justify-center p-8">
        <Loader2 className="h-6 w-6 animate-spin" />
      </div>
    );
  }

  if (error) {
    return <div className="text-destructive p-4">Error: {error.message}</div>;
  }

  return (
    <Card>
      <CardHeader>
        <CardTitle>Contracts</CardTitle>
      </CardHeader>
      <CardContent>
        <Table>
          <TableBody>
            {contracts?.map((contract) => (
              <TableRow 
                key={contract.id} 
                onClick={() => onSelect(contract)}
                className="cursor-pointer hover:bg-muted"
              >
                <TableCell>{contract.title}</TableCell>
                <TableCell>
                  <Badge variant={contract.status === 'completed' ? 'default' : 'secondary'}>
                    {contract.status}
                  </Badge>
                </TableCell>
              </TableRow>
            ))}
          </TableBody>
        </Table>
      </CardContent>
    </Card>
  );
}
```

## TypeScript Rules

- Add types for all Supabase table schemas via generated types
- Use interfaces for object shapes, types for unions
- Never use `any` — use `unknown` if truly unknown
- Import types from `@/types/database.types`
- Use generic Database type with Supabase client
